<P align=center><FONT face="arial, verdana"><I><A name=l26></A>26. To 
Pythocles</FONT></I>
<P align=center><FONT CLASS="ref"><B><A 
name=U161></A>[ U161 ]</FONT></B>
<P align=justify><B>Plutarch, <I>Against Colotes</I>, 29, p. 1124C: 
</B>The young are made flighty and headstrong by the one who writes of 
Pythocles, not yet eighteen, that in all of Greece there is no one more 
gifted and that his powers of expression are a prodigy, who writes that he 
himself is moved to pray as the women do <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">–</SPAN> that all 
that superiority of talent may not bring down on the young man’s head the 
jealously and resentment of heaven.
<P align=center><FONT CLASS="ref"><B><A 
name=U162></A>[ U162 ]</FONT></B>
<P align=justify><B><SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">Alciphron, 
<I>Letters (Letters of Courtesans),</I> </SPAN>II.2,3: </B>(cf.<FONT 
CLASS="orange"> </FONT><A 
href="#l21">above</A>)<B> 
</B>... he regards his Pythocles as an Alcibiades ...
<P align=center><FONT CLASS="ref"><B><A 
name=U163></A>[ U163 ]</FONT></B>
<P align=justify><B>Diogenes Laertius, <I>Lives of Philosophers,</I> 
X.6:</B> {Epicurus writes} in his letter to Pythocles: <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">"Hoist all sail, my 
dear boy, and steer clear of all culture." </SPAN>
<P align=justify><B>Plutarch, <I>On Listening to Lectures</I>, c.1, p. 
15D: </B>Shall we ... force them to put to sea in the Epicurean boat, and 
avoid poetry and steer their course clear of it?
<P align=justify><B>Plutarch, <I>That Epicurus actually makes a pleasant 
life impossible</I>, 12, p. 1094D: </B>Yet these men divert and alter the 
course of these pleasures, so great and numerous <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">–</SPAN> that never 
as it were, go dry <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">–</SPAN>&nbsp; and 
cut off their disciples from the taste; instead they tell some to <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">"hoist all sail" to 
escape from them.</SPAN>
<P style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0in; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0in" 
align=justify><B>Quintilian, <I>Institutio Oratoria, </I>XII.2.24:</B> In 
the first place, Epicurus banishes us from his presence without more ado, 
since he bids all his followers to fly from learning in the swiftest ship 
that they can find.
<P align=center><FONT CLASS="ref"><B><A 
name=U164></A>[ U164 ]</FONT></B>
<P align=justify><B>Plutarch, <I>That Epicurus actually makes a pleasant 
life impossible</I>, 12, p. 1094D: </B>Pythocles is urgently implored by 
all, men and women alike, in the person of Epicurus, not to set his heart 
on <SPAN CLASS="Ep1">"the 
so-called education of free men."</SPAN>
<P align=center><FONT CLASS="ref"><B><A 
name=U165></A>[ U165 ]</FONT></B>
<P align=justify><B>Diogenes Laertius, <I>Lives of Philosophers,</I> X.5: 
</B>And to the beautiful Pythocles he {Epicurus} writes: <SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">"</SPAN>I shall sit 
down and await your lovely and godlike appearance<SPAN 
CLASS="Ep1">."</SPAN>
